(verb
  :name "calc/line-integral"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/line-integral f-or-F curve [integrand-type]) -> scalar"
  :summary "Computes the line integral of a scalar or vector field over a closed curve using deterministic Simpson's rule."
  :explanation "A line integral integrates a field along a path. For a scalar field f, the integral is ∫f ds (arc length); for a vector field F, it is ∫F·dr (dot product of field and path tangent). calc/line-integral takes a field (lambda) and a curve closure (a parameterized path) and returns the integrated result. The integration uses Simpson's rule, which is deterministic and consistent across runs."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define circle (lambda (t) (list (cos (* 2 3.14159 t)) (sin (* 2 3.14159 t)) 0)))\n(define f (lambda (x y z) 1))\n(define arc-len (calc/line-integral f circle))\n(display arc-len)" :note "Integrate constant field 1 over a unit circle; result ≈ 2π")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define line (lambda (t) (list (* t 10) 0 0)))\n(define F (lambda (x y z) (list 1 0 0)))\n(define work (calc/line-integral F line 'vector))\n(display (list \"Work done:\" work))" :note "Compute work (line integral of force) along a straight path")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (circulation-in-field F)\n  (let ((circle (lambda (t)\n    (list (* 5 (cos (* 2 3.14159 t)))\n          (* 5 (sin (* 2 3.14159 t)))\n          0))))\n    (calc/line-integral F circle 'vector)))\n(define curl-field (lambda (x y z) (list (- y) x 0)))\n(let ((circ (circulation-in-field curl-field)))\n  (display (list \"Circulation (should be ≈ 50π):\" circ)))" :note "Compute circulation of a rotational field around a circle; should relate to curl")
  )
  :caveats ("Curve closure must return a 3-element list [x, y, z] for each parameter t ∈ [0, 1]." "Integration type ('scalar or 'vector) must match the field; scalar field with 'vector mode will misinterpret results." "Simpson's rule is accurate for smooth fields; discontinuous or very oscillatory fields may be approximated coarsely." "Result is deterministic within the device but subject to floating-point precision.")
  :drawbacks ("Fixed quadrature order (Simpson); no adaptive refinement for highly oscillatory fields." "Curve parameterization must be smooth; discontinuous jumps in the curve will produce spurious results." "No symbolic simplification; calling repeatedly for the same curve/field is inefficient." "Curve must be a closure; cannot directly pass analytic equations.")
  :usecases ("Physics: compute work done by a force along a trajectory." "Electromagnetism: evaluate Faraday's law ∮E·dr around a loop." "Fluid dynamics: measure circulation ∮v·dr around a vortex." "Complex analysis: integrate functions along contours (if restricted to 2-D).")
  :related ("calc/surface-integral" "calc/curl" "calc/divergence" "num/nintegrate-2d" "num/nintegrate-3d")
  :learn (:concept "Line integrals extend the idea of integration to curves in space; they measure the 'accumulation' of a field along a path." :prerequisites ("calculus / parametric curves" "lambda (to define fields and curves)") :progression "After calc/line-integral, explore calc/surface-integral to integrate over 2-D surfaces, and use both with Stokes' and divergence theorems.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A work-energy computation over a curved path needs ∫_γ F·dr; the operator supplies the path and the field and expects a scalar."
     :program "(define F (lambda (p) (list (car p) (cadr p))))\n(define x (lambda (t) t)) (define y (lambda (t) t))\n(calc/line-integral F x y 0 1)"
     :explanation "F = (x, y) along y = x from 0 to 1; ∫ = 1; operator sees ≈ 1."
     :meta "integral is 1-D over an interval; line-integral is 1-D over a curve in higher dimensions. Same idea, different geometry.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-nd; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'path integral of a field'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(define F (lambda (p) (list (car p) (cadr p))))")
       (:domain "work done along a sprite trajectory" :code "(motion/work-along-path field path)")
       (:domain "∫_γ F · dr" :code "∫_a^b F(γ(t)) · γ\\'(t) dt"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/line-integral in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''path integral of a field'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''path integral of a field'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/line-integral."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "For a conservative field F = ∇φ, the line integral depends only on endpoints (path independence)."
     :program "(define phi (lambda (p) (+ (* (car p) (car p)) (* (cadr p) (cadr p)))))\n(define F (lambda (p) (calc/gradient phi p)))\n(define x1 (lambda (t) t)) (define y1 (lambda (t) t))\n(define x2 (lambda (t) (* t t))) (define y2 (lambda (t) t))\n(< (abs (- (calc/line-integral F x1 y1 0 1) (calc/line-integral F x2 y2 0 1))) 0.05)"
     :invariant "F = ∇φ ⇒ ∫_γ F · dr = φ(γ(b)) - φ(γ(a))"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch15-multivariable-linear-algebra.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the calc-nd category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "calc/line-integral — see :summary."
     :composition "(define F (lambda (p) (list (- (cadr p)) (car p))))\n(define x (lambda (t) (cos t))) (define y (lambda (t) (sin t)))\n(calc/line-integral F x y 0 (* 2 3.14159))"
     :emergent "circulation"
     :meta "The emergent circulation belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Circulation = line integral around a closed loop; connected to curl by Stokes. See book-of-ml ch-01.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the calc-nd operations close into the circulation pattern."
     :cs "The emergent circulation is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "calc/newton"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/newton f x0 [tolerance iterations]) -> number"
  :summary "Finds a root of f using Newton's method, starting from initial guess x0."
  :explanation "Newton's method is an iterative algorithm: given a starting point x₀, repeatedly compute xₙ₊₁ = xₙ − f(xₙ)/f'(xₙ) until convergence. It converges rapidly (quadratic) near simple roots, but may diverge if started far away or near inflection points. This verb automates the iteration and returns the estimated root as a deterministic float."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(calc/newton (lambda (x) (- (* x x) 2)) 1.5)" :note "Finds a root of f(x) = x² − 2 (which is √2 ≈ 1.414); starting from 1.5 converges in few steps")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define f (lambda (x) (- (math/exp x) 3)))\n(define root (calc/newton f 1))\n(list 'root root 'check (f root))" :note "Finds root of eˣ = 3, which is ln(3); result ≈ 1.0986, and f(root) ≈ 0")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (find-roots-from-multiple-starts f starts)\n  (define (safe-newton x0)\n    (if (> (abs (calc/derivative f x0)) 0.01)\n        (calc/newton f x0)\n        '*diverged*))\n  (map safe-newton starts))\n(find-roots-from-multiple-starts (lambda (x) (- (* x x x) (* 2 x) 3))\n                                 '(0.5 1.5 2.5))" :note "Tries Newton from multiple starting points, filtering out cases where derivative is too small (risking division)")
  )
  :caveats ("Requires a nonzero derivative near the root; will fail if f'(x) ≈ 0" "Convergence is local: must start reasonably close to root (basin of attraction varies)" "May cycle or diverge if f has inflection points or multiple roots nearby" "Finds only one root; to find all roots, try multiple starting points" "Does not detect if root is a multiple root (converges slower there)")
  :drawbacks ("Requires computing f'(x) numerically at each iteration (2+ function calls per step)" "Sensitive to initial guess; poor choice leads to divergence or wrong root" "Does not bracket the root; no guaranteed convergence without good starting point" "Cannot find complex roots (only real-valued here)")
  :usecases ("Solving nonlinear equations where algebraic solution is impractical" "Finding equilibrium points in dynamical systems" "Solving implicit equations f(x) = c by shifting to f(x) − c = 0" "Machine learning: root-finding in optimization (alternative to gradient descent)")
  :related ("calc/derivative" "calc/limit" "calc/tangent-line")
  :learn (:concept "Iterative refinement using linear approximation (tangent line); quadratic convergence" :prerequisites ("calc/derivative" "calc/tangent-line") :progression "Master Newton for univariate roots, then explore multidimensional Newton via calc/jacobian")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A root-finding problem for a smooth f needs a fast iteration; Newton's method converges quadratically near a simple root."
     :program "(calc/newton (lambda (x) (- (* x x) 2)) 1.5)"
     :explanation "√2 ≈ 1.4142; operator sees a value very close to it."
     :meta "critical-points-1d finds where f' = 0; newton finds where f = 0. Different targets.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-1d; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'iterative root-finder using tangent lines'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(calc/newton (lambda (x) (- (* x x) 2)) 1.5)")
       (:domain "binary-search refinement of a fixed point" :code "(motion/binary-search-root f)")
       (:domain "Newton iteration" :code "x_{n+1} = x_n - f(x_n)/f\\'(x_n)"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/newton in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''iterative root-finder using tangent lines'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''iterative root-finder using tangent lines'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/newton."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Near a simple root, Newton's iteration converges quadratically: |x_{n+1} - r| ≤ C |x_n - r|²."
     :program "(define f (lambda (x) (- (* x x) 2)))\n(define r (calc/newton f 1.5))\n(< (abs (f r)) 0.0001)"
     :invariant "Near simple root r: |x_{n+1} - r| ≤ C |x_n - r|²"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-10 (Numerical Methods).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the calc-1d category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "calc/newton — see :summary."
     :composition "(define f (lambda (x) (- (* x x x) x 1)))\n(define seeds (list 1 -1 0.5))\n(map (lambda (s) (calc/newton f s)) seeds)"
     :emergent "root-finder"
     :meta "The emergent root-finder belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Newton is the archetype quadratically-convergent iteration. See book-of-ml ch-06 for the descent-analog.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the calc-1d operations close into the root-finder pattern."
     :cs "The emergent root-finder is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "calc/partial"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/partial f i point) -> number"
  :summary "Computes the i-th partial derivative ∂f/∂xᵢ at a given point using central differences."
  :explanation "A partial derivative measures how a multivariable function changes when one variable changes while others stay fixed. This verb evaluates the derivative with respect to the i-th coordinate: perturbs point by small step h in that coordinate only, then applies the central-difference formula. Returns a scalar float deterministically, making it building-block for gradient, Hessian, Laplacian, and Jacobian."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define f (lambda (p) (+ (* 2 (car p)) (expt (cadr p) 2))))\n(calc/partial f 0 '(3 4))\n(calc/partial f 1 '(3 4))" :note "f(x,y) = 2x + y²; ∂f/∂x = 2 everywhere, ∂f/∂y = 2y; results ≈ 2 and ≈ 8")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define f (lambda (p) (* (car p) (cadr p))))\n(define pt '(2 3))\n(list 'partial-x (calc/partial f 0 pt)\n      'partial-y (calc/partial f 1 pt))" :note "f(x,y) = xy; ∂f/∂x = y, ∂f/∂y = x; at (2,3) results ≈ 3 and ≈ 2")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (numeric-gradient f point)\n  (let ((dims (length point)))\n    (map (lambda (i) (calc/partial f i point))\n         (map (lambda (k) k) (range 0 dims)))))\n(define f (lambda (p) (apply + (map (lambda (x) (expt x 2)) p))))\n(numeric-gradient f '(1 2 3))" :note "Builds full gradient ∇f manually; f(x,y,z) = x²+y²+z² has ∇f = (2x, 2y, 2z); result ≈ (2, 4, 6)")
  )
  :caveats ("Index i must be valid for the point (0-indexed, less than length)" "Numeric approximation; assumes f is smooth enough near point" "Step size h is fixed at ~1e-5; may be too large or small for extremely flat/steep functions" "Point must be a list of numbers; f must accept and return a number")
  :drawbacks ("Requires three function evaluations (center, forward, backward) per partial" "Becomes expensive for high-dimensional optimization (n partials = 3n function calls)" "Central difference is O(h²) accurate but requires h small (affects condition number)" "Does not detect or warn about discontinuities")
  :usecases ("Building blocks for gradients (calc/gradient) and optimization algorithms" "Verifying symbolic derivatives numerically" "Computing sensitivities: how output changes with respect to each input" "Estimating heat flow or chemical concentrations in PDEs")
  :related ("calc/gradient" "calc/hessian" "calc/laplacian" "calc/directional-derivative" "calc/jacobian")
  :learn (:concept "Partial derivatives as directional change along coordinate axes; central-difference approximation" :prerequisites ("calc/derivative") :progression "Master calc/partial, then use it with calc/gradient and calc/hessian for optimization")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A partial-derivative-with-respect-to-one-variable is what backpropagation needs to build the gradient component-by-component."
     :program "(define f (lambda (p) (+ (* (car p) (car p)) (* (cadr p) (cadr p)))))\n(calc/partial f 0 (list 1 2))"
     :explanation "∂f/∂x at (1, 2) = 2x = 2; operator sees ≈ 2."
     :meta "gradient is the full vector; partial is one component. Use partial when you don't need the whole vector.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-nd; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'axis-aligned rate of change'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(define f (lambda (p) (+ (* (car p) (car p)) (* (cadr p) (cadr p)))))")
       (:domain "per-channel color derivative" :code "(shader/dcolor-dc chan p)")
       (:domain "∂f/∂x_i" :code "partial derivative"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/partial in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''axis-aligned rate of change'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''axis-aligned rate of change'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/partial."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "For f ∈ C^2, the mixed partials commute: ∂²f/∂x∂y = ∂²f/∂y∂x."
     :program "(define f (lambda (p) (* (car p) (cadr p))))\n(define fx (lambda (p) (calc/partial f 0 p)))\n(define fxy (lambda (p) (calc/partial fx 1 p)))\n(define fy (lambda (p) (calc/partial f 1 p)))\n(define fyx (lambda (p) (calc/partial fy 0 p)))\n(< (abs (- (fxy (list 1 1)) (fyx (list 1 1)))) 0.05)"
     :invariant "f ∈ C^2 ⇒ ∂²f/∂x∂y = ∂²f/∂y∂x"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch15-multivariable-linear-algebra.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the calc-nd category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "calc/partial — see :summary."
     :composition "(define f (lambda (p) (+ (* (car p) (car p)) (* (cadr p) (cadr p)))))\n(list (calc/partial f 0 (list 1 1)) (calc/partial f 1 (list 1 1)) (calc/gradient f (list 1 1)))"
     :emergent "gradient-component"
     :meta "The emergent gradient-component belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Partial + assemble = gradient; the building block of every autodiff engine.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
