     :cs "The emergent gradient-component is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "calc/radius-of-convergence"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/radius-of-convergence coeffs) -> (radius . interval) | (escalate 'fuel-budget)"
  :summary "Computes the radius and interval of convergence for a power series Σc(n)xⁿ using the ratio test."
  :explanation "A power series Σc(n)xⁿ converges for |x| < R, where R is the radius of convergence. calc/radius-of-convergence takes a list of coefficients [c(0), c(1), c(2), ...] and applies the ratio test (lim |c(n+1)/c(n)|) to determine R. It returns a pair (radius . interval), where interval is a list giving the convergence domain. This is useful for understanding the domain where a power series approximation is valid."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define exp-coeffs (list 1 1 (/ 1 2) (/ 1 6) (/ 1 24) (/ 1 120)))\n(define radius-result (calc/radius-of-convergence exp-coeffs))\n(display radius-result)" :note "Radius of convergence for e^x series (coefficients 1/n!); should be infinite")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define geo-coeffs (list 1 1 1 1 1 1))\n(let ((roc (calc/radius-of-convergence geo-coeffs)))\n  (if (pair? roc)\n    (display (list \"Radius:\" (car roc) \"Interval:\" (cdr roc)))\n    (escalate 'convergence-failed geo-coeffs)))" :note "Geometric series 1 + x + x² + ... has radius 1; check the pair structure")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (analyze-series coeffs name)\n  (let ((roc (calc/radius-of-convergence coeffs)))\n    (cond ((eq? roc 'diverged) (display (list name \"series diverges everywhere\")))\n          ((pair? roc)\n            (let ((radius (car roc))\n                  (interval (cdr roc)))\n              (display (list name \"converges for x in\" interval))\n              (if (> radius 10) (display \"(very large radius; nearly entire domain)\"))\n              interval))\n          (else (escalate 'fuel-budget name)))))\n(analyze-series '(1 2 6 24 120) 'factorial-based)" :note "Robust series analysis; handle different outcomes (convergent, divergent, fuel-exhausted)")
  )
  :caveats ("Coefficients list must contain at least 2 elements; empty or single-element lists may escalate." "Ratio test assumes non-zero coefficients; exact zeros can cause division-by-zero or false results." "The test is asymptotic; for finite coefficient lists, results are approximations." "Very large coefficient sequences can exhaust the fuel budget before reaching a stable ratio; escalate 'fuel-budget in that case." "Result is deterministic within the device but may differ across platforms due to floating-point arithmetic.")
  :drawbacks ("Does not determine convergence behavior AT the boundary (|x| = R); Dirichlet/Abel tests required for those points." "Assumes the series is a power series in a single variable; multivariable or non-power series will give meaningless results." "No symbolic simplification; repeated calls for the same series are wasteful." "Ratio test is not always fastest; Cauchy root test might converge faster for some series but is not used here.")
  :usecases ("Verify that a Taylor series approximation is valid over a desired domain." "Determine the region of validity for a power-series solution to a differential equation." "Analyze the behavior of generating functions in combinatorics." "Validate numerical approximations before deployment.")
  :related ("calc/surface-integral" "calc/divergence" "calc/curl" "num/nintegrate-2d")
  :learn (:concept "The radius of convergence is a fundamental property of power series; it determines the domain where the series is a valid approximation of its limit function." :prerequisites ("power series / Taylor series" "ratio test (calculus)") :progression "After computing radius of convergence, use the series for numerical approximation within that radius, or explore other series tests (root test, Dirichlet) for behavior at the boundary.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A power-series computation needs to know how far around the base point it converges; operating outside R gives nonsense."
     :program "(calc/radius-of-convergence (lambda (n) (/ 1.0 (factorial n))))"
     :explanation "Coefficients 1/n! give R = ∞ (exp series); operator sees a very large value."
     :meta "series-converges? tests one specific series; radius-of-convergence gives the whole disk of convergence at once.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: series; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'domain of validity of a series expansion'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(calc/radius-of-convergence (lambda (n) (/ 1.0 (factorial n))))")
       (:domain "trust-region size around a Taylor approximation" :code "(motion/trust-radius-of-approx approx)")
       (:domain "R = 1/limsup |a_n|^{1/n}" :code "Cauchy-Hadamard formula"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/radius-of-convergence in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''domain of validity of a series expansion'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''domain of validity of a series expansion'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/radius-of-convergence."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Inside |x-c| < R the series converges absolutely; outside it diverges."
     :program "(define geo (lambda (n) 1.0))\n(define R (calc/radius-of-convergence geo))\n(< 0.5 R)"
     :invariant "R = 1/limsup |a_n|^{1/n}"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-03 (Sequences, Series, Recurrence).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the series category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
