     :composition "(define coeffs (list (lambda (n) (/ 1.0 (factorial n))) (lambda (n) 1.0)))\n(map calc/radius-of-convergence coeffs)"
     :emergent "convergence-disk"
     :meta "The emergent convergence-disk belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Radius of convergence + Taylor series is the standard function-approximation pattern.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the series operations close into the convergence-disk pattern."
     :cs "The emergent convergence-disk is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "calc/riemann-sum"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/riemann-sum f a b kind n) -> number"
  :summary "Approximates the definite integral ∫ₐᵇ f(x)dx using Riemann sums with rectangles."
  :explanation "A Riemann sum estimates the area under a curve by dividing the interval [a,b] into n rectangles and summing their areas. The kind parameter controls rectangle height: 'left uses left endpoints, 'right uses right endpoints, 'mid uses midpoints. Left and right sums bracket the true integral (for monotone functions); midpoint is more accurate. This verb is foundational for understanding integration and is useful when symbolically computing the integral is intractable."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(calc/riemann-sum (lambda (x) (* x x)) 0 1 'mid 100)" :note "∫₀¹ x² dx = 1/3 ≈ 0.333; midpoint with 100 subintervals gives good approximation")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define f (lambda (x) (math/exp (- (* x x)))))\n(calc/riemann-sum f -2 2 'mid 500)" :note "Gaussian bell curve; ∫₋₂² e^(−x²) dx ≈ 1.76; use more subintervals for better accuracy")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (convergence-test f a b kind)\n  (map (lambda (n) (list 'n n 'sum (calc/riemann-sum f a b kind n)))\n       '(10 50 100 500 1000)))\n(convergence-test (lambda (x) (sin x)) 0 3.14159 'mid)" :note "Tests how Riemann sum converges as n increases; shows that midpoint converges faster than left/right")
  )
  :caveats ("Accuracy depends on n: more rectangles = better approximation but slower computation" "Left and right sums are biased; 'mid is more accurate but not always best for oscillating functions" "Does not detect or handle discontinuities in f on [a,b]" "Parameter order: f, a (lower limit), b (upper limit), kind (symbol), n (integer subintervals)")
  :drawbacks ("O(1/n) convergence: need n~1000s for 3–4 decimal places (slow compared to Simpson's rule)" "Does not work well for f with sharp peaks or discontinuities" "Left/right sums give different results; need to use both to bracket the true integral" "For smooth functions, calc/integral (Simpson) is significantly faster")
  :usecases ("Teaching integration: visualizing how area is approximated by rectangles" "Estimating probability (area under density curve) when symbolic form is unknown" "Computing work or energy in physics (∫ F·dx)" "Baseline accuracy check when implementing advanced quadrature")
  :related ("calc/integral" "calc/average-value" "calc/arc-length" "calc/volume-revolution")
  :learn (:concept "Riemann sums as foundation of the Riemann integral; convergence via refinement" :prerequisites () :progression "Master Riemann sums with 'mid kind, then move to calc/integral for faster Simpson's rule")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A pedagogy or budget check needs an explicit Riemann sum with a chosen mesh, so the operator can compare left/right/midpoint approximations."
     :program "(calc/riemann-sum (lambda (x) (* x x)) 0 1 100)"
     :explanation "100 rectangles for ∫₀¹ x² dx ≈ 0.33; operator sees a value near 0.333."
     :meta "calc/integral hides the mesh; calc/riemann-sum exposes it. Use riemann-sum when the mesh matters (education, controlled experiment).")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-1d; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'discrete approximation of a continuous accumulation'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(calc/riemann-sum (lambda (x) (* x x)) 0 1 100)")
       (:domain "audio RMS from samples" :code "(audio/rms samples)")
       (:domain "Riemann sum" :code "Σ f(x_i) Δx_i"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/riemann-sum in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''discrete approximation of a continuous accumulation'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''discrete approximation of a continuous accumulation'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/riemann-sum."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "As mesh size → 0, the Riemann sum → the Riemann integral (for continuous f)."
     :program "(define f (lambda (x) (* x x)))\n(< (abs (- (calc/riemann-sum f 0 1 1000) (calc/integral f 0 1))) 0.01)"
     :invariant "lim_{n→∞} (1/n) Σ_i f(a + iΔx)Δx = ∫_a^b f"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch13-calculus-1 and ch14-calculus-2.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the calc-1d category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "calc/riemann-sum — see :summary."
     :composition "(define f (lambda (x) (* x x)))\n(map (lambda (n) (calc/riemann-sum f 0 1 n)) (list 10 100 1000))"
     :emergent "mesh-refinement-sequence"
     :meta "The emergent mesh-refinement-sequence belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Mesh refinement → convergent sum = the classical numerical integration pattern.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the calc-1d operations close into the mesh-refinement-sequence pattern."
     :cs "The emergent mesh-refinement-sequence is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "calc/second-derivative"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/second-derivative f x) -> number"
  :summary "Computes the second derivative f''(x) using central differences, measuring curvature."
  :explanation "The second derivative describes how fast the slope is changing: how curved the graph is at a point. Positive f''(x) means the curve is concave up (bending upward); negative means concave down. The second derivative is used to classify critical points (local max/min via second derivative test), estimate errors in Taylor approximations, and solve differential equations. Numerically computed via central-difference formula on the first-derivative approximation."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(calc/second-derivative (lambda (x) (expt x 3)) 1)\n(calc/second-derivative (lambda (x) (expt x 3)) -1)" :note "f(x) = x³ has f''(x) = 6x; at x=1 result ≈ 6, at x=−1 result ≈ −6")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (classify-critical-point f x0)\n  (let ((fpp (calc/second-derivative f x0)))\n    (cond ((> fpp 0.01) 'local-minimum)\n          ((< fpp -0.01) 'local-maximum)\n          (else 'inconclusive))))\n(classify-critical-point (lambda (x) (- (* x x) (* 4 x))) 2)" :note "f(x) = x² − 4x; critical point at x=2; f''(2) = 2 > 0 so it's a local minimum")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (filter pred xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc '()))\n    (cond ((null? xs) (reverse acc))\n          ((pred (car xs)) (loop (cdr xs) (cons (car xs) acc)))\n          (else (loop (cdr xs) acc)))))\n(define (find-inflection-points f a b n)\n  (define h (/ (- b a) n))\n  (define pts (map (lambda (k) (+ a (* k h))) (range 0 n)))\n  (filter (lambda (x) (if (< x (- b h)) \n                          (let ((fpp-left (calc/second-derivative f (- x h)))\n                                (fpp-right (calc/second-derivative f (+ x h))))\n                            (< (* fpp-left fpp-right) 0))\n                          #f))\n          pts))\n(find-inflection-points (lambda (x) (expt x 5)) -1 1 20)" :note "Finds inflection points where f''(x) changes sign; x⁵ has one at x=0")
  )
  :caveats ("Numeric approximation; accuracy depends on h and function smoothness" "May be noisy on nearly-linear functions (f''(x) ≈ 0 across range)" "If f'(x) is discontinuous, f''(x) will be very noisy or unreliable" "Central-difference formula requires evaluating f at three points; does not reuse derivative calculations")
  :drawbacks ("More expensive than first derivative (3 function evaluations vs. implicit reuse)" "Amplifies numerical noise: if f is given by finite-precision data, f'' is noisier than f'" "Does not detect or handle jump discontinuities in f' (where f'' is undefined)" "For piecewise smooth functions, may give misleading results near kinks")
  :usecases ("Second derivative test: classifying critical points as local max, min, or saddle" "Detecting concavity changes (inflection points)" "Estimating truncation error in Taylor approximations (error ≈ f''(ξ)·h³/6)" "Studying oscillation damping in mechanics (f'' = acceleration in x = position)")
  :related ("calc/derivative" "calc/extrema-1d" "calc/hessian" "calc/taylor")
  :learn (:concept "Second derivative as curvature; concavity and inflection points" :prerequisites ("calc/derivative") :progression "Use calc/second-derivative for univariate optimization, then calc/hessian for multivariate")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "An inflection-point analysis or curvature computation needs f''(x); the operator wants a direct call rather than differentiating twice manually."
     :program "(define f (lambda (x) (* x x x)))\n(define ddf (calc/second-derivative f))\n(ddf 1)"
     :explanation "f'' of x³ at 1 is 6; operator sees ≈ 6."
     :meta "derivative gives f'; second-derivative gives f''. Composition (calc/derivative (calc/derivative f)) works too but is noisier.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-1d; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'second-order rate of change'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(define f (lambda (x) (* x x x)))")
       (:domain "acceleration from position samples" :code "(motion/acceleration samples t)")
       (:domain "second derivative f\\'\\'(x)" :code "d²f/dx²"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/second-derivative in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''second-order rate of change'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''second-order rate of change'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/second-derivative."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "At a local max, f'' ≤ 0; at a local min, f'' ≥ 0 (second-derivative test)."
     :program "(define f (lambda (x) (* x x)))\n(define ddf (calc/second-derivative f))\n(> (ddf 0) 0)"
     :invariant "local min at c ⇒ f''(c) ≥ 0  ∧  local max at c ⇒ f''(c) ≤ 0"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch13-calculus-1 and ch14-calculus-2.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the calc-1d category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "calc/second-derivative — see :summary."
     :composition "(define f (lambda (x) (sin x)))\n(define ddf (calc/second-derivative f))\n(map ddf (list 0 (/ 3.14159 2) 3.14159))"
     :emergent "convexity-test"
     :meta "The emergent convexity-test belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Second-derivative test = classical convexity analysis; extended in book-of-ml ch-06 (gradient descent).")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the calc-1d operations close into the convexity-test pattern."
     :cs "The emergent convexity-test is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "calc/series-converges?"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/series-converges? coeff-fn [opts]) -> 'converges | 'diverges | 'inconclusive"
  :summary "Apply the ratio test to a series Σa(n) and return convergence verdict."
  :explanation "The ratio test is a standard tool in analysis: if lim |a(n+1)/a(n)| = L, then the series converges absolutely if L < 1, diverges if L > 1, and is inconclusive if L = 1. This verb computes that limit numerically via finite differences and returns one of three symbolic outcomes. Use it to classify infinite series before attempting to work with them. The verdict is deterministic within the precision of the device."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(calc/series-converges? (lambda (n) (/ 1 (+ n 1))))" :note "Harmonic series 1/n diverges; ratio test → 'inconclusive (limit ratio = 1, edge case)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(calc/series-converges? (lambda (n) (/ 1 (* 2 n))))" :note "Geometric-like series with ratio 1/2 < 1 → 'converges")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(let ((test-series (lambda (n) (/ (factorial n) (expt 2 n)))))\n  (cond ((equal? (calc/series-converges? test-series) 'converges)\n         (display \"safe to sum\"))\n        (else (display \"risky or inconclusive\"))))" :note "Factorial grows faster than exponential, so ratio → ∞ → 'diverges; guards downstream computation")
  )
  :caveats ("The ratio test is inconclusive when lim(ratio) = 1; the verb returns 'inconclusive in that case, not a boolean" "Requires a coefficient function, not a pre-computed list; the function is called repeatedly to build ratios" "Numerical precision limits detection at extremes; very slow convergence or divergence may be misclassified" "The verb does not sum the series; it only predicts convergence. Use calc/line-integral, calc/surface-integral, or num/nintegrate-* for actual computation")
  :drawbacks ("Ratio test fails silently on edge cases (L = 1); other tests (root test, integral test) may succeed where ratio test is inconclusive" "Expensive if the coefficient function is costly to evaluate" "Limited to scalar series; vector/matrix series require different machinery")
  :usecases ("Before summing a power series, check convergence to avoid infinite loops" "Validate that a Fourier series representation is mathematically sound" "Classify solutions to differential equations that are given as series")
  :related ("calc/radius-of-convergence" "calc/line-integral" "calc/surface-integral" "num/nintegrate-2d" "num/nintegrate-3d")
  :learn (:concept "Ratio test as a tool for series classification; how symbolic outcomes encode mathematical uncertainty" :prerequisites ("(core)/lambda") :progression "Move to calc/radius-of-convergence to analyze power series; then to num/nintegrate-* to compute definite integrals")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A summation over an infinite series needs a pre-check: does the series converge at all, or is the computation meaningless?"
     :program "(list (calc/series-converges? (lambda (n) (/ 1.0 (* n n))))\n      (calc/series-converges? (lambda (n) (/ 1.0 n))))"
     :explanation "Σ 1/n² converges (π²/6); Σ 1/n diverges (harmonic); operator sees (#t #f)."
     :meta "radius-of-convergence is for power series; series-converges? is for a single numeric series. Different domains.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: series; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'convergence gate for infinite sums'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(list (calc/series-converges? (lambda (n) (/ 1.0 (* n n))))")
       (:domain "idle-loop bounded-effect check" :code "(motion/effect-bounded? loop)")
       (:domain "convergence of Σ a_n" :code "lim_{N→∞} Σ_{n=1}^N a_n exists"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/series-converges? in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''convergence gate for infinite sums'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''convergence gate for infinite sums'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/series-converges?."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "If Σ a_n converges then a_n → 0 (necessary condition)."
     :program "(define diverges (lambda (n) 1.0))\n(not (calc/series-converges? diverges))"
     :invariant "Σ a_n converges ⇒ lim_{n→∞} a_n = 0"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch-advanced-03 (Sequences, Series, Recurrence).")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the series category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
