)

(verb
  :name "calc/surface-integral"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/surface-integral surface-fn field-fn mode [opts]) -> number | error"
  :summary "Integrate a scalar field or vector field over a parametric surface."
  :explanation "A surface integral generalizes single-variable integration to two-dimensional surfaces embedded in 3D (or lower). Two modes: 'scalar integrates a scalar function f over surface area dS; 'flux integrates a vector field F's normal component (F · n) over the surface, measuring flow. The surface is defined parametrically, and the verb uses numerical quadrature (tensor Simpson's rule) to approximate the integral. Essential in physics (flux through a membrane, work on a surface) and engineering."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(calc/surface-integral\n  (lambda (u v) (list u v (+ u v)))  ;; surface: z = u + v\n  (lambda (x y z) 1)                   ;; scalar field f = 1\n  'scalar)" :note "Integrating constant 1 over a planar surface gives its area")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(calc/surface-integral\n  (lambda (u v) (list (* (cos u) (sin v)) (* (sin u) (sin v)) (cos v)))  ;; unit sphere\n  (lambda (x y z) (+ (* x x) (* y y) (* z z)))                          ;; f = x² + y² + z²\n  'scalar)" :note "On a sphere, x² + y² + z² = 1, so the integral should be surface area 4π")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (flux-through-cylinder h r)\n  (calc/surface-integral\n    (lambda (theta z) (list (* r (cos theta)) (* r (sin theta)) z))  ;; cylinder\n    (lambda (x y z) (list x y 0))  ;; radial outward field F = (x, y, 0)\n    'flux))\n(flux-through-cylinder 2 1)" :note "Flux of outward field through cylinder wall (height 2, radius 1); integrates outward normal component; expect 4π")
  )
  :caveats ("Requires a parametric surface function (u, v) → [x, y, z], not an implicit surface z = f(x, y)" "'scalar mode integrates over dS (magnitude of normal); 'flux mode integrates F · n (oriented normal)" "The parametrization's domain (u, v ranges) must be specified in opts or defaults to [0, 1] × [0, 1]" "Quadrature may fail or return high error if the surface is singular or the field is discontinuous")
  :drawbacks ("Numerical integration cost grows with required precision; complex surfaces or fine meshes are expensive" "'flux mode requires an oriented surface; non-orientable surfaces (e.g., Möbius band) give undefined results" "No symbolic simplification; cannot exploit symmetry automatically")
  :usecases ("Compute electric flux through a conductor surface using Gauss's law" "Integrate mass distribution over a curved membrane" "Verify divergence theorem: compare surface integral of F·n against volume integral of ∇·F")
  :related ("calc/curl" "calc/divergence" "calc/line-integral" "num/nintegrate-2d" "num/nintegrate-3d")
  :learn (:concept "Surface integrals as flux and scalar measures; parametric representation of surfaces; oriented vs. unoriented" :prerequisites ("(core)/lambda" "calc/divergence" "calc/curl") :progression "After surface integrals, explore divergence theorem and Stokes' theorem by comparing surface and volume/line integrals")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A flux computation through a curved surface needs ∫∫_S F·dS; the operator wants a scalar output for the total flow."
     :program "(define F (lambda (p) (list (car p) (cadr p) (caddr p))))\n(define x (lambda (u v) (* (cos u) (sin v))))\n(define y (lambda (u v) (* (sin u) (sin v))))\n(define z (lambda (u v) (cos v)))\n(calc/surface-integral F x y z 0 (* 2 3.14159) 0 3.14159)"
     :explanation "Flux of position field through unit sphere = 4π; operator sees ≈ 12.57."
     :meta "line-integral is 1D over a curve; surface-integral is 2D over a surface. Same idea, different dimensionality.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-nd; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'flux through a 2D surface'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(define F (lambda (p) (list (car p) (cadr p) (caddr p))))")
       (:domain "rendered lighting integral over a mesh" :code "(render/light-through-mesh mesh)")
       (:domain "∫∫_S F · dS" :code "∫∫ F · (r_u × r_v) du dv"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/surface-integral in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''flux through a 2D surface'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''flux through a 2D surface'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/surface-integral."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "For a closed surface enclosing volume V, ∫∫_S F·dS = ∫∫∫_V div F dV (Divergence theorem)."
     :program "(define F (lambda (p) (list (car p) (cadr p) (caddr p))))\n(define x (lambda (u v) (* (cos u) (sin v))))\n(define y (lambda (u v) (* (sin u) (sin v))))\n(define z (lambda (u v) (cos v)))\n(define flux (calc/surface-integral F x y z 0 (* 2 3.14159) 0 3.14159))\n(< (abs (- flux (* 4 3.14159))) 0.5)"
     :invariant "∮_S F · dS = ∫_V div F dV"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch15-multivariable-linear-algebra.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the calc-nd category."
