(verb
  :name "calc/surface-revolution"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/surface-revolution f a b) -> number"
  :summary "Computes the surface area when the curve y=f(x) is rotated about the x-axis from a to b."
  :explanation "Rotating a curve around an axis creates a surface (like a vase or barrel). The surface area is given by the formula S = ∫ₐᵇ 2πy √(1 + (dy/dx)²) dx. This verb computes the integral numerically, combining function values and derivative estimates. It appears in engineering (tank capacity), physics (moment of inertia), and design (volume/material estimates)."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(calc/surface-revolution (lambda (x) 1) 0 2)" :note "Rotating y=1 (horizontal line) about x-axis from 0 to 2 gives a cylinder; surface area = 2π·1·2 = 4π ≈ 12.57")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define f (lambda (x) (sqrt x)))\n(calc/surface-revolution f 0 4)" :note "Rotating y=√x from 0 to 4 creates a cone-like surface; computed area is deterministic float")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (compare-solids-of-revolution)\n  (define line (lambda (x) 1))\n  (define cone (lambda (x) (/ x 2)))\n  (define parab (lambda (x) (sqrt x)))\n  (list 'cylinder (calc/surface-revolution line 0 2)\n        'cone (calc/surface-revolution cone 0 2)\n        'parabola (calc/surface-revolution parab 0 2)))\n(compare-solids-of-revolution)" :note "Compares surface areas for different curves rotated about x-axis; cone grows faster than line, parabola curves differently")
  )
  :caveats ("Formula assumes rotation about the x-axis; rotation about y-axis or other axes requires manual transformation" "f(x) must be non-negative on [a,b] for geometric interpretation (negative y is allowed but interpreted as mirror)" "Requires f to be differentiable; near discontinuities or sharp corners, results are unreliable" "Does not handle self-intersecting or discontinuous curves well")
  :drawbacks ("Expensive: requires computing f and f' at many quadrature points" "Sensitive to spikes in |f'(x)|: steep sections dominate the integrand √(1 + f'²)" "If f oscillates rapidly, accuracy can degrade; use higher tolerance or refine mesh" "Does not visualize the surface; must interpret numeric result as area")
  :usecases ("Engineering: computing surface area of tanks, pipes, and pressure vessels" "Physics: calculating moments of inertia and electromagnetic fields on axisymmetric bodies" "Manufacturing: estimating material needed (paint, coating) for rotational parts" "Design optimization: minimizing surface area (cost) subject to volume constraints")
  :related ("calc/volume-revolution" "calc/arc-length" "calc/integral" "calc/derivative")
  :learn (:concept "Surface area element dS = 2πy ds in polar/rotational coordinates; integration of arc length weighted by radius" :prerequisites ("calc/integral" "calc/derivative" "calc/arc-length") :progression "Master surface-revolution, then explore calc/volume-revolution for volume-equivalent solids")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A cup or lampshade area estimation needs the surface generated by rotating y=f(x) about the x-axis; the audit wants a single integral answer."
     :program "(calc/surface-revolution (lambda (x) x) 0 1)"
     :explanation "Surface area of cone y=x, 0≤x≤1 is π√2; operator sees ≈ 4.44."
     :meta "arc-length gives length of a curve; surface-revolution gives area of the surface swept out. Different quantities, both come from the same arc-length integrand.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-1d; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'2D area from a rotating 1D curve'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(calc/surface-revolution (lambda (x) x) 0 1)")
       (:domain "scene-mesh-area of a lathe object" :code "(mesh/lathe-area profile)")
       (:domain "∫ 2π f(x) √(1 + f\\'(x)²) dx" :code "surface of revolution"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/surface-revolution in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''2D area from a rotating 1D curve'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''2D area from a rotating 1D curve'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/surface-revolution."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Surface area is non-negative and monotone in the interval [a, b]."
     :program "(define f (lambda (x) x))\n(<= (calc/surface-revolution f 0 1) (calc/surface-revolution f 0 2))"
     :invariant "∀ [a, b] ⊆ [c, d]. sr(f, a, b) ≤ sr(f, c, d)"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch14-calculus-2.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the calc-1d category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
