(verb
  :name "calc/tangent-line"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/tangent-line f a) -> (list slope intercept)"
  :summary "Computes the tangent line to the curve y=f(x) at x=a, returning (slope, intercept) as an a-list."
  :explanation "The tangent line is the best linear approximation to a curve at a point. Its slope is f'(a) and it passes through (a, f(a)), so its equation is y = f'(a)(x − a) + f(a). The verb returns this in slope-intercept form: (m, b) where m = f'(a) and b is the y-intercept. Tangent lines are used to linearize nonlinear functions, initialize iterative solvers (Newton's method), and visualize instantaneous rates of change."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define x (lambda args (list \"x\" args)))\n(define =x^2 '=x^2)\n(define f (lambda (x) (* x x)))\n(calc/tangent-line f 2)\n(list 'at-x=2 'f(x)=x^2 'tangent 'has 'slope 4)" :note "f(x) = x²; at x=2, f(2)=4 and f'(2)=4; tangent line has slope 4 and passes through (2,4)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define f (lambda (x) (sin x)))\n(define (pt) (calc/tangent-line f (/ 3.14159 2)))\n(define tline (pt))\n(list 'tangent-to-sin-at-pi/2 tline)\n(list 'slope (car tline) 'intercept (cadr tline))" :note "sin(x) at x=π/2; f(π/2)=1, f'(π/2)=0, so tangent is horizontal: (0, 1)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (linear-approx f a dx)\n  (let ((tline (calc/tangent-line f a)))\n    (let ((m (car tline)) (b (cadr tline)))\n      (let ((x-new (+ a dx)))\n        (let ((y-approx (+ (* m x-new) b))\n              (y-actual (f x-new)))\n          (list 'x x-new 'linear-approx y-approx 'actual y-actual 'error (- y-actual y-approx)))))))\n(linear-approx (lambda (x) (math/exp x)) 0 0.1)" :note "Uses tangent line at x=0 to approximate e^0.1; error is small for small dx")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns a-list (list of two elements); destructure as (m . b) or access via car/cadr" "Tangent line is only accurate near a; error grows as you move away from x=a" "If f'(a) is poorly behaved (very large or near zero), tangent may be vertical or horizontal" "Does not detect or warn about corners or discontinuities at a")
  :drawbacks ("Requires computing f(a) and f'(a); not cached, so subsequent queries recompute" "Approximation error is O(Δx²) in distance from a; unusable far from tangent point" "Linear approximation ignores higher-order curvature; for worse accuracy, use Taylor series (calc/taylor)" "Does not handle parameterized or implicit curves directly")
  :usecases ("Newton's method: using tangent line to iteratively find roots" "Linearization: approximating nonlinear models near an operating point (engineering)" "Visualization: drawing tangent vectors on curves in graphing software" "Error analysis: bounding approximation error in scientific computing")
  :related ("calc/derivative" "calc/newton" "calc/taylor" "calc/limit")
  :learn (:concept "Linear approximation and the tangent line as first-order Taylor polynomial" :prerequisites ("calc/derivative") :progression "Understand tangent lines, then use them in calc/newton and extend to calc/taylor for higher-order approximations")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "Newton's method needs the tangent line at a point; a plot annotator also needs a callable tangent for drawing."
     :program "(define f (lambda (x) (* x x)))\n(define tan (calc/tangent-line f 1))\n(list (tan 1) (tan 2))"
     :explanation "Tangent at (1, 1) is y = 2x - 1; at x=1, value 1; at x=2, value 3; operator sees (1 3)."
     :meta "derivative gives f'; tangent-line gives the affine function y = f'(a)(x-a) + f(a). Different granularity.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-1d; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'first-order local approximation'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(define f (lambda (x) (* x x)))")
       (:domain "linear approximation of a control curve" :code "(curve/tangent-at spline t)")
       (:domain "tangent line" :code "y = f\\'(a)(x-a) + f(a)"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/tangent-line in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''first-order local approximation'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''first-order local approximation'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/tangent-line."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "The tangent line at a agrees with f at a and has the same derivative: tan(a) = f(a) and tan'(a) = f'(a)."
     :program "(define f (lambda (x) (* x x x)))\n(define a 1)\n(define tan (calc/tangent-line f a))\n(and (< (abs (- (tan a) (f a))) 0.001)\n     (< (abs (- ((calc/derivative tan) a) ((calc/derivative f) a))) 0.05))"
     :invariant "tan(a) = f(a)  ∧  tan\\'(a) = f\\'(a)"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch13-calculus-1 and ch14-calculus-2.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the calc-1d category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "calc/tangent-line — see :summary."
     :composition "(define f (lambda (x) (* x x)))\n(map (lambda (a) ((calc/tangent-line f a) (+ a 0.1)))\n     (list 0 1 2))"
     :emergent "linear-approximation"
     :meta "The emergent linear-approximation belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Tangent line = degree-1 Taylor polynomial; higher-order via calc/taylor.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the calc-1d operations close into the linear-approximation pattern."
     :cs "The emergent linear-approximation is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "calc/taylor"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/taylor f a n) -> list"
  :summary "Compute the Taylor polynomial of degree n for function f about point a, returned as coefficient list with low-order terms first."
  :explanation "A Taylor polynomial approximates a smooth function near a point by matching the function's value and all its derivatives up to a given order. This verb builds the polynomial coefficients: the constant term f(a), then f'(a), f''(a)/2!, etc. The result is a list where index i holds the coefficient of (x−a)^i, making it easy to evaluate near a by walking the list with powers. Essential for numerical approximation, physics simulation, and understanding local behavior of curves."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define f (lambda (x) (* x x)))\n(calc/taylor f 0 3)\n;; → (0 0 2 0) — x² has zero constant, zero linear, 2 quadratic, zero cubic" :note "Quadratic function around 0 produces exactly its coefficients; higher-order terms vanish.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (pow x y) (expt x y))\n(define (fold-left f init xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc init))\n    (if (null? xs) acc (loop (cdr xs) (f acc (car xs))))))\n(define (sin-approx x)\n  (let ((poly (calc/taylor (lambda (t) (sin t)) 0 5)))\n    (fold-left (lambda (acc i)\n      (+ acc (* (list-ref poly i) (pow x i))))\n      0 (list 0 1 2 3 4 5))))\n(sin-approx 0.5)\n;; ≈ 0.479 (close to sin(0.5) ≈ 0.479)" :note "Build a polynomial evaluator from the Taylor coefficients; 5th-order captures sine well near 0.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (pow x y) (expt x y))\n(define (fold-left f init xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc init))\n    (if (null? xs) acc (loop (cdr xs) (f acc (car xs))))))\n(define (adaptive-approx f a x-val orders)\n  ;; Try successive orders, return first that converges well\n  (let loop ((n 1) (prev-val 0))\n    (if (> n orders)\n      prev-val\n      (let* ((poly (calc/taylor f a n))\n             (val (fold-left (lambda (acc i)\n               (+ acc (* (list-ref poly i) (pow (- x-val a) i))))\n               0 (range n))))\n        (if (< (abs (- val prev-val)) 0.000001)\n          val\n          (loop (+ n 1) val))))))\n(adaptive-approx (lambda (t) (exp t)) 0 0.2 10)" :note "Practical strategy: compute Taylor series iteratively until convergence; avoids over-computing unnecessary terms.")
  )
  :caveats ("Accuracy depends on distance from a; polynomial diverges rapidly far from the expansion point." "Numerical differentiation may accumulate rounding error; use higher precision or symbolic input if available." "High-degree polynomials can exhibit Runge's phenomenon (wild oscillation) if not evaluated carefully.")
  :drawbacks ("Linear cost in degree n; impractical for very high orders." "Only good approximation in a neighborhood of a, not globally." "If f is discontinuous or non-smooth, derivatives do not exist and the method fails.")
  :usecases ("Physics: approximate acceleration near a point without expensive function calls." "Numerics: seed Newton's method or other rootfinding with a quadratic model." "Visualization: cheaply sample a smooth curve at many points by caching the Taylor polynomial.")
  :related ("calc/derivative" "calc/tangent-line" "calc/newton")
  :learn (:concept "Local polynomial approximation via derivative values; the foundation of all calculus-based numerical methods." :prerequisites ("calc/derivative") :progression "Apply Taylor series in calc/newton for root-finding, or in calc/arc-length for accurate curvature estimates.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "An analytic approximation for a complicated function around a point needs the Taylor polynomial of chosen degree so the caller can trade accuracy for cost."
     :program "(calc/taylor (lambda (x) (exp x)) 0 3)"
     :explanation "Third-degree Taylor of exp around 0 is 1 + x + x²/2 + x³/6; operator sees the polynomial coefficients."
     :meta "tangent-line is degree 1; taylor is any degree. Use taylor for higher-order accuracy.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-1d; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'polynomial approximation via derivatives'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(calc/taylor (lambda (x) (exp x)) 0 3)")
       (:domain "N-th-order motion prediction" :code "(motion/predict-order state n)")
       (:domain "Taylor polynomial T_n(x) = Σ f^{(k)}(a)/k! (x-a)^k" :code "Taylor formula"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/taylor in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''polynomial approximation via derivatives'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''polynomial approximation via derivatives'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/taylor."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
