)

(verb
  :name "calc/total-differential"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/total-differential f a dv) -> number"
  :summary "Approximate the change in f near point a when input moves by displacement dv, using the gradient: df ≈ ∇f(a) · dv."
  :explanation "The total differential extends the single-variable derivative to multivariable functions. Rather than asking 'what is f at a?', it asks 'if we nudge the input by a small vector dv, by how much does f change?' The answer is the dot product of the gradient ∇f at a with dv. This is the best linear approximation to the change, exact to first order. Used everywhere: optimization (finding descent directions), physics (work = force · displacement), and numerical methods (predictor–corrector steps)."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define f (lambda (xy) (+ (* (car xy) (car xy)) (* (cadr xy) (cadr xy)))))\n;; f is x² + y²; at a = (1, 2), try dv = (0.01, 0.01)\n(calc/total-differential f (list 1 2) (list 0.01 0.01))\n;; ≈ 0.06 (gradient is (2x, 2y) = (2, 4), dot (0.01, 0.01) = 0.06)" :note "Linear approximation predicts change without recomputing f at the new point.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (surface-height lat lon) (+ (* 0.5 lat) (* 0.3 lon)))\n(define base-pos (list 40.7 -74.0))\n(define step (list 0.001 0.001))\n(define dh (calc/total-differential surface-height base-pos step))\n(display (list \"Height change over small step:\" dh))\n;; \"Height change over small step: \" 0.0008" :note "Estimate elevation change when moving slightly north and east; avoids redundant height lookups.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (gradient-descent f a learning-rate steps)\n  (let loop ((pos a) (i 0))\n    (if (>= i steps)\n      pos\n      (let ((grad (calc/gradient f pos)))\n        (let ((step-vec (map (lambda (g) (* (- learning-rate) g)) grad)))\n          (let ((new-pos (map + pos step-vec)))\n            (loop new-pos (+ i 1))))))))\n;; Or, at each step, use total-differential to estimate new f value before moving:\n(define (approx-step f pos lr)\n  (let ((grad (calc/gradient f pos)))\n    (let ((delta (map (lambda (g) (* (- lr) g)) grad)))\n      (let ((est-df (calc/total-differential f pos delta)))\n        (list (map + pos delta) est-df)))))\n(approx-step (lambda (xy) (+ (* (car xy) (car xy)) (* (cadr xy) (cadr xy))))\n  (list 1.0 1.0) 0.01)" :note "Estimate function decrease before taking a full step; useful for adaptive step sizing or line search.")
  )
  :caveats ("Only accurate for small displacements dv; error grows quadratically with |dv|." "Requires the gradient at a; if f is non-smooth or poorly conditioned, the approximation fails." "If dv is not small, use calc/taylor (2nd-order) or numerical integration instead.")
  :drawbacks ("Linear approximation only; quadratic or higher-order effects are ignored." "Computing the gradient itself requires partial derivatives; cost scales with dimension." "Does not warn if the displacement is too large; you must validate a posteriori.")
  :usecases ("Optimization: gradient descent and Newton's method both rely on total differential reasoning." "Physics: work, energy, and flux calculations all use differential approximations." "Numerical PDE solvers: predictor–corrector schemes use total differential for one-step prediction.")
  :related ("calc/gradient" "calc/derivative" "calc/taylor")
  :learn (:concept "First-order linear approximation in multiple dimensions; the gateway to multivariable calculus and optimization." :prerequisites ("calc/gradient" "calc/derivative") :progression "Combine with calc/taylor for higher-order accuracy, or use iteratively in gradient descent.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A change-propagation estimate needs df = Σ ∂f/∂x_i dx_i — the first-order linear response of f to a perturbation."
     :program "(define f (lambda (p) (+ (* (car p) (car p)) (* (cadr p) (cadr p)))))\n(calc/total-differential f (list 1 1) (list 0.01 0.02))"
     :explanation "df ≈ 2·0.01 + 2·0.02 = 0.06; operator sees ≈ 0.06."
     :meta "gradient is ∇f; total-differential applies the gradient to a specific perturbation vector. gradient(f) · dx.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-nd; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'linear-response to a small perturbation'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(define f (lambda (p) (+ (* (car p) (car p)) (* (cadr p) (cadr p)))))")
       (:domain "error-propagation over a sensor sum" :code "(sensor/error-propagate sensors deltas)")
       (:domain "df = ∇f · dx" :code "total differential"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/total-differential in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''linear-response to a small perturbation'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''linear-response to a small perturbation'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/total-differential."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "df is linear in the perturbation dx: total-differential(f, x, av + bw) = a·df(v) + b·df(w)."
     :program "(define f (lambda (p) (+ (* (car p) (car p)) (* (cadr p) (cadr p)))))\n(define x (list 1 1))\n(define v (list 0.1 0)) (define w (list 0 0.1))\n(< (abs (- (calc/total-differential f x (list 0.2 0.3))\n           (+ (* 2 (calc/total-differential f x v))\n              (* 3 (calc/total-differential f x w))))) 0.01)"
     :invariant "df(av + bw) = a·df(v) + b·df(w)"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch15-multivariable-linear-algebra.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the calc-nd category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "calc/total-differential — see :summary."
     :composition "(define f (lambda (p) (* (car p) (cadr p))))\n(define x (list 1 2))\n(define errs (list (list 0.01 0) (list 0 0.01) (list 0.01 0.01)))\n(map (lambda (d) (calc/total-differential f x d)) errs)"
     :emergent "error-budget"
     :meta "The emergent error-budget belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Total differential = first-order error propagation; used in every measurement pipeline.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the calc-nd operations close into the error-budget pattern."
     :cs "The emergent error-budget is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

(verb
  :name "calc/volume-revolution"
  :library "calc"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(calc/volume-revolution f a b axis) -> number"
  :summary "Compute the volume of a solid formed by rotating the curve y=f(x) about the x-axis or y-axis between x=a and x=b, using the disk method."
  :explanation "When you rotate a curve around an axis, you sweep out a 3D solid. Slice the solid perpendicular to the axis, and each slice is a disk (or washer). The disk-method formula integrates the area of each disk: rotating y=f(x) about the x-axis gives V = ∫π[f(x)]² dx from a to b. This verb evaluates that integral numerically. Essential for engineering (modeling tanks, shafts, rotated profiles) and physics (computing moments of inertia)."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(define f (lambda (x) (sqrt x)))\n;; Rotate y=√x from x=0 to x=4 about the x-axis\n(calc/volume-revolution f 0 4 'x)\n;; ≈ 8π (exact answer for this solid)" :note "Simple function; disk method is exact for powers and roots.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (cone-profile x) (* 0.5 x))  ;; y = 0.5x: cone of height h, base r=0.5h\n(define cone-vol (calc/volume-revolution cone-profile 0 3 'x))\n(display (list \"Cone volume (h=3):\" cone-vol))\n;; ≈ 2.36 (exact: (1/3)πr²h = (1/3)π(1.5)²(3) = 2.25π)" :note "Linear profile generates a cone; use this to verify design dimensions.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (design-tank target-vol height)\n  ;; Find profile f such that rotating f about x-axis gives desired volume\n  ;; Use bisection to search for the scaling factor\n  (let ((base-profile (lambda (x) (* 0.2 (sqrt (+ 1 (* 0.5 x)))))))\n    (let loop ((scale-low 0.5) (scale-high 2.0))\n      (if (< (- scale-high scale-low) 0.001)\n        scale-low\n        (let* ((scale-mid (/ (+ scale-low scale-high) 2.0))\n               (scaled-f (lambda (x) (* scale-mid (base-profile x))))\n               (vol (calc/volume-revolution scaled-f 0 height 'x)))\n          (if (< vol target-vol)\n            (loop scale-mid scale-high)\n            (loop scale-low scale-mid)))))))\n(define tank-scale (design-tank 100 5))\n(display (list \"Tank scale factor:\" tank-scale))" :note "Invert the integral: given a target volume, find the profile that achieves it via bisection.")
  )
  :caveats ("Assumes f(x) ≥ 0 throughout [a, b]; negative values will compute as positive area (distance to axis)." "Only handles solid-of-revolution about one of the two coordinate axes; general axis rotation requires a coordinate change." "Numerical integration error depends on smoothness of f; discontinuities or sharp corners reduce accuracy.")
  :drawbacks ("Quadrature cost scales with required accuracy; smooth functions integrate faster than oscillatory ones." "Disk method is inefficient for certain shapes (e.g., thin shells); washer or shell method may be cheaper for some geometries." "No symbolic output; if exact form is needed, use symbolic integration (outside Motoi).")
  :usecases ("Engineering: tank and pipe design, computing exact volumes from CAD profiles." "Physics: moment of inertia for rotating machinery (I ∝ ∫ r² dm)." "Architecture: dome and barrel-vault volume under a given profile.")
  :related ("calc/integral" "calc/arc-length" "calc/surface-revolution")
  :learn (:concept "The disk method: slicing a solid perpendicular to an axis and integrating cross-sectional areas." :prerequisites ("calc/integral") :progression "Compare with calc/surface-revolution for surface area; learn shell method separately for other geometries.")
  :row-2-audit (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:problem "A vessel-capacity computation needs the volume swept out by rotating y=f(x) about the x-axis."
     :program "(calc/volume-revolution (lambda (x) x) 0 1)"
     :explanation "Cone y=x, 0≤x≤1 has volume π/3 ≈ 1.047; operator sees ≈ 1.047."
     :meta "surface-revolution gives the area; volume-revolution gives the enclosed volume. Same rotation, different quantity.")
    (:eng "The operator gets one line per call; failure surfaces the exact input that broke the expectation."
     :math "Category: calc-1d; the verb operates within its declared algebraic type."
     :cs "Complexity as declared in the signature; deterministic and testable."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "'3D volume from a rotating 1D curve'"
     :rungs (
       (:domain "calc native" :code "(calc/volume-revolution (lambda (x) x) 0 1)")
       (:domain "lathe object volume" :code "(mesh/lathe-volume profile)")
       (:domain "π ∫ f(x)² dx" :code "disk method volume"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is calc/volume-revolution in its native library. Rung 2 shows the same ''3D volume from a rotating 1D curve'' shape in a metaphor domain. Rung 3 lifts the shape into a math/logical setting where the transfer is formal. Recognizing the same shape in all three lets the reader carry the verb's intuition into problems Motoi does not directly cover."
     :meta "The shape transfers because ''3D volume from a rotating 1D curve'' is substrate-independent — the same relationship holds whenever the underlying category admits the required structure.")
    (:eng "Engineers who have met the shape elsewhere already know when to reach for calc/volume-revolution."
     :math "The shape is captured by a small equation set; each rung is a model of that equation set."
     :cs "Once the shape is named, the same algorithm skeleton (traverse, close, compare) applies at each rung."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Volume is non-negative and monotone in the interval [a, b]."
     :program "(define f (lambda (x) x))\n(<= (calc/volume-revolution f 0 1) (calc/volume-revolution f 0 2))"
     :invariant "∀ [a, b] ⊆ [c, d]. vr(f, a, b) ≤ vr(f, c, d)"
     :meta "The invariant is the algebraic essence of the verb; a single counter-example would falsify it and prove the implementation broken. See book-of-math ch14-calculus-2.")
    (:eng "The runnable claim doubles as a CI smoke test — if the invariant ever prints #f, the verb has drifted."
     :math "The invariant is the defining property in the calc-1d category."
     :cs "Property-based test: the program above is a runnable falsifier candidate for a QuickCheck-style fuzzer."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:base "calc/volume-revolution — see :summary."
     :composition "(define f (lambda (x) x))\n(list (calc/arc-length f 0 1) (calc/surface-revolution f 0 1) (calc/volume-revolution f 0 1))"
     :emergent "lathe-metric-triple"
     :meta "The emergent lathe-metric-triple belongs to the family of composed behaviours where one verb's output feeds the next verb's input, and the pair carries meaning neither verb has alone. Arc-length + surface + volume = lathe geometry triple; used together in CAD.")
    (:eng "The composition is short enough to inline in a callsite yet meaningful enough to name and reuse."
     :math "Under composition, the calc-1d operations close into the lathe-metric-triple pattern."
     :cs "The emergent lathe-metric-triple is a first-class named pattern; recognize it once and it reappears everywhere."))
)

